21:17.877 --> 21:20.980 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY MOUNT, Public Policy
Institute of
California: Well, ultimately,
what the big

21:21.080 --> 21:24.316 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
fear was, that there would be an
uncontrolled
release from the reservoir.

21:24.416 --> 21:29.889 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The worst nightmare of a
reservoir engineer
is to not be able to control the
water behind

21:29.989 --> 21:31.724 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the reservoir.

21:31.824 --> 21:35.961 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the emergency spillway, had
it failed
and had it collapsed, would
basically have

21:36.061 --> 21:37.997 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
lowered the lake level by almost
30 feet.

21:38.097 --> 21:42.768 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that is a tremendous amount
of water in
a short period of time, which
would have resulted

21:42.868 --> 21:44.670 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
in catastrophic flooding
downstream.

21:44.770 --> 21:48.607 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So the basic
issue here,
obviously, as we reported, is
too much rain,

21:48.707 --> 21:51.076 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
too much snow, which I know is a
good thing
in California normally.

21:51.177 --> 21:52.912 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY MOUNT: Yes.

21:53.012 --> 21:55.948 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: But what is it
with regards
to the engineering that went
wrong here?

21:56.048 --> 21:58.551 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY MOUNT: Well, so, we have
a couple
of things.

21:58.651 --> 22:03.522 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
You have to remember that
California reservoirs
are under tension all the time.

22:03.622 --> 22:05.124 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We use them to store water.

22:05.224 --> 22:08.194 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, of course, we're just
coming out of a
record drought.

22:08.294 --> 22:11.030 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We store water, but we also use
them to regulate
floods.

22:11.130 --> 22:14.567 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So you have to set aside some
space behind
the reservoir.

22:14.667 --> 22:18.904 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And in this case, there's not
much space set
behind this reservoir to catch
floods.

22:19.004 --> 22:20.139 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
So, it filled.

22:20.239 --> 22:21.974 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And it filled pretty quickly.

22:22.074 --> 22:24.543 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And then we had to run water
down a spillway.

22:24.643 --> 22:28.414 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we were forced to allow
water to go over
an emergency spill which had
never been tested

22:28.514 --> 22:32.318 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
since the Oroville was built in
1968.

22:32.418 --> 22:35.821 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And things didn't go well when
the water went
over the spillway.

22:35.921 --> 22:40.859 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So we ended up with basically,
what you can
consider the fog of war in a
flood event.

22:40.960 --> 22:43.829 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You never quite know what is
going to happen.

22:43.929 --> 22:49.001 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And water has a way of testing
all the shortcomings
of your design and your actions.

22:49.101 --> 22:50.803 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And it did so in Oroville.

22:50.903 --> 22:54.206 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, as we
reported, there
is a hole that was carved out of
the main

22:54.306 --> 22:57.676 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
spillway and concrete was
basically ripped
part by the volume of water.

22:57.776 --> 22:59.011 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY MOUNT: Right.

22:59.111 --> 23:00.479 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: How are they
addressing
that issue now?

23:00.579 --> 23:02.615 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY MOUNT: Well, they're not
addressing
it now.

23:02.715 --> 23:04.483 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
They can't.

23:04.583 --> 23:06.819 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They can't do anything about it
because they
are running 100,000 cubic feet
per second

23:06.919 --> 23:09.521 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of water down that spillway now.

23:09.622 --> 23:14.994 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They will be able to address it
this summer,
and they don't know now what
they are going

23:15.094 --> 23:16.095 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to do about it.

23:16.195 --> 23:18.430 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But they have lost almost half
of that spillway.

23:18.530 --> 23:22.601 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Just the power of water tore it
to pieces
and moved it on down into the
river downstream.

23:22.701 --> 23:27.006 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There is really nothing they can
do today
about that spillway.

23:27.106 --> 23:28.907 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They have to use it.

23:29.008 --> 23:32.811 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: We mentioned
that there
had been some concerns raised
about the earthen

23:32.911 --> 23:37.283 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
berm that is underneath the
auxiliary spillway.

23:37.383 --> 23:39.084 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Why is it that that wasn't
shored up?

23:39.184 --> 23:41.887 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Did people just not see that
this was going
to possibly be an issue?

23:41.987 --> 23:45.858 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY MOUNT: No, I'm sure
people thought
it was an issue at the time.

23:45.958 --> 23:50.729 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But you are always faced with,
how much money
are you going to spend to
address something

23:50.829 --> 23:54.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that you think is going to be a
very, very
rare event?

23:54.433 --> 23:59.405 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's actually what happens
in reservoir
design, dam design anywhere.

23:59.505 --> 24:04.643 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You can spend an infinite amount
of money
to mitigate the most improbable
things, but

24:04.743 --> 24:06.745 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
there still is a probability.

24:06.845 --> 24:12.685 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think the big thing, big
takeaway here when
you look at this is that the
engineers probably

24:12.785 --> 24:18.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
dismissed the idea of coating
that hillside
in concrete, because it would be
very, very

24:18.857 --> 24:21.960 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
expensive to mitigate something
that was highly
unlikely to happen.

24:22.061 --> 24:24.296 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it never happened before in
the dam's
history.

24:24.396 --> 24:26.165 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Well, now it happened.

24:26.265 --> 24:31.136 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, frankly, all our climate
projections
for the future are suggesting
these kind of

24:31.236 --> 24:34.840 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
events might be more frequent
and even more
intense.

24:34.940 --> 24:41.313 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, for us here in California,
this is a bit
of a time to reflect on what we
are asking

24:41.413 --> 24:45.517 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
our reservoirs to do and how we
manage them
and how we're going to prepare
for the future.

24:45.617 --> 24:49.555 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right,
Jeffrey Mount
of the Public Policy Institute
of California,

24:49.655 --> 24:51.423 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
thank you so much.

24:51.523 --> 24:57.629 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY MOUNT: Thank you.

24:57.730 --> 25:08.006 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now: a rare look
at life under
the rule of the Nigerian
militant group Boko

25:08.107 --> 25:11.243 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Haram, as filmed by the group
itself.

25:11.343 --> 25:16.281 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Audie Cornish of NPR's "All
Things Considered"
recorded this conversation for
us last week.

25:16.382 --> 25:20.285 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AUDIE CORNISH: Last year, Voice
of America
News Service, which is funded by
the U.S.

25:20.386 --> 25:25.224 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
government, received a stunning
trove of videos
from Nigeria, 18 hours of
footage recorded

25:25.324 --> 25:28.394 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
by Boko Haram's own cameras in
2014.

25:28.494 --> 25:30.496 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
The pictures comes from
Northeastern Nigeria.

25:30.596 --> 25:34.867 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, at the time, Boko Haram had
total control
of the region.

25:34.967 --> 25:40.039 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The videos take us behind Boko
Haram's assault
on the Nigerian military and
into villages

25:40.139 --> 25:42.841 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
where their leaders administer
rough justice.

25:42.941 --> 25:47.112 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
VOA has produced a series of
four reports
based on the videos.

25:47.212 --> 25:52.084 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And joining me to talk about
what we can learn
from these images is VOA's
Ibrahim Ahmed.

25:52.184 --> 25:55.788 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He hosts a weekly program for
their service
broadcast in Nigeria.

25:55.888 --> 25:57.055 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Thank you for joining us.

25:57.156 --> 25:58.957 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
IBRAHIM AHMED, Voice of America:
It's my pleasure.

25:59.057 --> 26:02.895 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AUDIE CORNISH: Now, tell us a
little bit about
how you were able to verify
these videos.

26:02.995 --> 26:10.502 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
IBRAHIM AHMED: When the Voice of
America got
these videos, first of all, we
sat down and

26:10.602 --> 26:13.138 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
went through almost all of them.

26:13.238 --> 26:19.044 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we were able to determine
that they came
from not Northeastern Nigeria
because the

26:19.144 --> 26:24.683 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
people in the videos speak in
Kanuri, which
is the predominant language
there, and which

26:24.783 --> 26:31.290 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is also the language of most of
the Boko Haram
leadership and the members.

26:31.390 --> 26:33.125 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That was the first thing.

26:33.225 --> 26:39.798 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Then there are references to
Boko Haram and
to events that only Boko Haram
will know,

26:39.898 --> 26:43.769 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
like the attacks carried in some
areas of
Northeastern Nigeria.

26:43.869 --> 26:49.341 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AUDIE CORNISH: Your reporting
shows a couple
of things, one, the faces of
some leaders

26:49.441 --> 26:53.645 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and participates in Boko Haram,
which I understand
is very uncommon.

26:53.745 --> 27:02.788 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It also shows how they are able
to basically
bring whole villages into their
ideology using

27:02.888 --> 27:04.289 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
violence.

27:04.389 --> 27:08.594 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And in one clip, there is a
tribunal where
they exert their justice.

27:08.694 --> 27:10.462 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
How do these tribunals work?

27:10.562 --> 27:16.935 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
IBRAHIM AHMED: Well, in order to
control the
people, when Boko Haram captures
a place and

27:17.035 --> 27:21.507 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they want to bring people in
line, they will
hold these kind of tribunals.

27:21.607 --> 27:27.246 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they will force everybody
from the village
or the town to attend the
tribunals.

27:27.346 --> 27:33.018 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They will bring people they're
accusing, whether
they are drug users or drug
sellers, according

27:33.118 --> 27:34.920 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to them.

27:35.020 --> 27:40.292 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They will bring them to these
tribunals, and
they will read out a statement
that you are

27:40.392 --> 27:42.060 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
guilty of this or guilty of
that.

27:42.160 --> 27:43.629 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Do you accept your guilt?

27:43.729 --> 27:45.497 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Well, if you accept it, fine.

27:45.597 --> 27:47.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You just go and lay down and get
killed.

27:47.733 --> 27:52.037 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AUDIE CORNISH: They do something
similar with
young boys and men who they
conscript into

27:52.137 --> 27:53.839 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
fighting.

27:53.939 --> 27:58.577 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
You have a video that is
unusual, in that
it shows a Boko Haram leader
basically getting

27:58.677 --> 28:01.313 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
everyone to gear up to fight.

28:01.413 --> 28:03.148 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Let's watch that.

28:03.248 --> 28:09.888 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NARRATOR: Awaz (ph) says the
best of the martyrs
are those that fight in the
front.

28:09.988 --> 28:12.691 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They are the ones who do not
turn back until
they are killed.

28:12.791 --> 28:21.099 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
IBRAHIM AHMED: When Boko Haram
started in
2009, initially, their
membership were made

28:21.199 --> 28:25.771 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
up of the original followers of
the (INAUDIBLE)
Boko Haram.

28:25.871 --> 28:31.143 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But when they started capturing
territory,
they started conscripting
people.

28:31.243 --> 28:36.481 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AUDIE CORNISH: There is video of
a failed
attack, essentially, on an army
barracks.

28:36.582 --> 28:38.884 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And you see fighters looking for
weapons.

28:38.984 --> 28:42.588 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You see fighters not necessarily
able to use
the weapons they have.

28:42.688 --> 28:45.724 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
What are the fighting
capabilities of Boko
Haram at this point?

28:45.824 --> 28:52.397 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
IBRAHIM AHMED: Initially, Boko
Haram was kind
of going into fights with the
military with

28:52.497 --> 28:56.301 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
much more powerful weapons then
what the military
had.

28:56.401 --> 29:04.810 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The military had AK-47 rifles,
while the militants
come with heavy machine guns,
anti-aircraft

29:04.910 --> 29:05.811 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
guns.

29:05.911 --> 29:08.380 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, the military had to run away
at the time.

29:08.480 --> 29:17.022 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But, in 2015, the present
government in Nigeria,
when they started taking the
fight to Boko

29:17.122 --> 29:22.861 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Haram, they were able to adapt
themselves
and to get those kind of weapons
that Boko

29:22.961 --> 29:24.763 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Haram was using on them.

29:24.863 --> 29:29.501 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that is when they started
winning the
war and kicking Boko Haram out
of these major

29:29.601 --> 29:31.069 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
cities and towns.

29:31.169 --> 29:33.538 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AUDIE CORNISH: Do you feel as
though these
are areas that can rebuild?

29:33.639 --> 29:40.579 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
IBRAHIM AHMED: It is possible,
but it's going
to be really difficult, because
the crisis

29:40.679 --> 29:46.385 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or the carnage that Boko Haram
has done in
the area is just unbelievable.

29:46.485 --> 29:50.856 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AUDIE CORNISH: Ibrahim Ahmed of
Voice of America,
thank you so much for speaking
with us.

29:50.956 --> 29:54.226 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
IBRAHIM AHMED: Thank you so
much.

29:54.326 --> 29:59.364 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
My pleasure.

29:59.464 --> 30:09.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: As we near the
gruesome sixth
anniversary of the war in Syria,
daily documents

30:09.541 --> 30:12.244 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of the carnage there now flood
the Internet.

30:12.344 --> 30:17.849 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Photos and videos posted by both
civilians
and combatants catalogue the
shocking depths

30:17.949 --> 30:21.553 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of human cruelty and possible
war crimes.

30:21.653 --> 30:27.059 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now human rights investigators
are increasingly
turning to the Internet to track
what's happening,

30:27.159 --> 30:29.995 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
not only in Syria, but in other
conflict zones.

30:30.095 --> 30:35.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As part of our Breakthroughs
coverage of invention
and innovation, special
correspondent Cat

30:35.500 --> 30:41.973 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Wise reports on a new university
program training
students to become human rights
investigators

30:42.074 --> 30:43.275 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in the digital age.

30:43.375 --> 30:47.045 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And a warning: This story
contains some disturbing
images.

30:47.145 --> 30:53.285 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CAT WISE: For decades, human
rights investigators
have relied on tools like
shovels and backhoes

30:53.385 --> 30:59.357 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to uncover mass graves and mass
atrocities
in places like Bosnia, Iraq, and
Rwanda.

30:59.458 --> 31:05.464 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But in today's smartphone-filled
world, videos
and images of people killed or
suffering thousands

31:05.564 --> 31:11.670 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of miles away take only a couple
of clicks
to find on YouTube, Facebook,
Twitter.

31:11.770 --> 31:16.341 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The front lines of human rights
work have
shifted in the digital age, and
a new generation

31:16.441 --> 31:19.845 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of investigators is beginning to
employ high-tech
tools.

31:19.945 --> 31:22.013 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
STUDENT: We can probably
screen-shot that.

31:22.114 --> 31:23.014 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
STUDENT: Yes.

31:23.115 --> 31:24.015 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
STUDENT: And reverse-image it.

31:24.116 --> 31:25.350 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
STUDENT: Yes.

31:25.450 --> 31:26.284 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STUDENT: And we should look up
the name of
that pharmacy.

31:26.384 --> 31:28.286 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
STUDENT: Can anyone translate
that?

